hands_on_practices.solution:
We begin from the fundamental work-conjugacy definition $W=\tfrac{1}{2}\,\boldsymbol{\sigma}:\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}$ and the isotropic linear constitutive law $\boldsymbol{\sigma}=2\mu\,\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}+\lambda\,\mathrm{tr}(\boldsymbol{\varepsilon})\,\mathbf{I}$. For the specified pure shear state, the only nonzero strain components are $\varepsilon_{12}=\varepsilon_{21}=\gamma/2$, so $\mathrm{tr}(\boldsymbol{\varepsilon})=0$. Hence, by the constitutive law, the only nonzero stress components are $\sigma_{12}=\sigma_{21}=2\mu\,\varepsilon_{12}=2\mu\,(\gamma/2)=\mu\,\gamma$.

The correct strain energy density is

$$
W=\tfrac{1}{2}\,\boldsymbol{\sigma}:\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}
= \tfrac{1}{2}\sum_{i=1}^{3}\sum_{j=1}^{3}\sigma_{ij}\,\varepsilon_{ij}
= \tfrac{1}{2}\bigl(2\,\sigma_{12}\,\varepsilon_{12}\bigr)
= \sigma_{12}\,\varepsilon_{12}
= (\mu\,\gamma)\left(\tfrac{\gamma}{2}\right)
= \tfrac{\mu\,\gamma^{2}}{2}.
$$


Next, we evaluate the “incorrect” energy $W_{\mathrm{V}}=\tfrac{1}{2}\,\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}_{\mathrm{V}}^{\mathsf{T}}\mathbf{C}_{\mathrm{V}}\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}_{\mathrm{V}}$ under the unscaled Voigt mapping. For the given pure shear, the Voigt strain vector has only its sixth component nonzero: $\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}_{\mathrm{V}}=[\,0,\,0,\,0,\,0,\,0,\,\varepsilon_{12}\,]^{\mathsf{T}}$ with $\varepsilon_{12}=\gamma/2$. Consistency with $\boldsymbol{\sigma}=2\mu\,\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}$ on shear implies the associated Voigt stiffness satisfies $(\mathbf{C}_{\mathrm{V}})_{66}=2\mu$, so that $\sigma_{12}=(\mathbf{C}_{\mathrm{V}})_{66}\,\varepsilon_{12}=2\mu\,\varepsilon_{12}$. Therefore,

$$
W_{\mathrm{V}}
= \tfrac{1}{2}\,\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}_{\mathrm{V}}^{\mathsf{T}}\mathbf{C}_{\mathrm{V}}\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}_{\mathrm{V}}
= \tfrac{1}{2}\,\varepsilon_{12}\,(2\mu)\,\varepsilon_{12}
= \mu\,\varepsilon_{12}^{2}
= \mu\left(\tfrac{\gamma}{2}\right)^{2}
= \tfrac{\mu\,\gamma^{2}}{4}.
$$


The ratio of the incorrectly computed energy to the correct energy is thus

$$
r := \frac{W_{\mathrm{V}}}{W}
= \frac{\tfrac{\mu\,\gamma^{2}}{4}}{\tfrac{\mu\,\gamma^{2}}{2}}
= \tfrac{1}{2}.
$$


This factor-of-two discrepancy arises because the unscaled Voigt mapping uses the Euclidean inner product in $\mathbb{R}^{6}$, which does not coincide with the tensor inner product on symmetric second-order tensors: off-diagonal components contribute twice in $\boldsymbol{\sigma}:\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}$ but only once in $\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}_{\mathrm{V}}^{\mathsf{T}}\boldsymbol{\sigma}_{\mathrm{V}}$. A norm-preserving mapping, such as the Kelvin mapping that scales shear components by $\sqrt{2}$, restores $W=\tfrac{1}{2}\,\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}_{\mathrm{K}}^{\mathsf{T}}\mathbf{C}_{\mathrm{K}}\,\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}_{\mathrm{K}}$ exactly.
